title: 9News Sydney | Friday December 12 | Full Episode
description: Mark Burrows leads the bulletin with the tragic car crash involving medical student Lydia Fa'amau, an innocent victim fighting for her life in Liverpool Hospital after a police pursuit crash, with a 17-year-old allegedly behind the wheel of a stolen ute facing charges. Next, "Crocodile Wrangler" Matt Wright has been sentenced to 10 months in prison and a $5,000 fine for attempting to pervert the course of justice in relation to a 2022 fatal helicopter crash, though he has filed an appeal. In politics, the Albanese government has committed hundreds of millions to save 1,000 jobs at Tomago Aluminium with subsidised energy, while state Health Ministers reject a $23 billion hospital funding deal, demanding more from the Commonwealth to address bed block and aged care issues. The Prime Minister is also under pressure, ordering a review of parliamentary entitlements following a spending scandal. The bulletin also covers a Sydney court case where the CEO of Wahlburgers Australia, Sam Mustaca, was found guilty of two counts of common assault against an employee, which was captured on CCTV. Other segments include the guilty plea of a former childcare worker/police officer, an emotional defense from the parents of convicted rapist Tom Silvagni, a chaotic near-miss in Carlingford traffic, an unusual surge in flu cases driven by a new variant, and preparations for a busy Christmas holiday travel period at Sydney Airport. title: 9News Adelaide | Friday December 12 | Full Episode
description: Alice Monfries leads the Adelaide news with shocking security footage of a dramatic peak-hour van crash in Prospect, and the subsequent rush by witnesses to help the miraculously uninjured driver. Road safety is addressed with the announcement of new mobile detection cameras targeting distracted drivers in Valley View and Felixstow, with no initial grace period for fines. The video features the emotional court proceedings for Tom Silvagni, where his parents publicly maintain his innocence, while his victim bravely confronts him. Separately, the sentencing of a truck driver, Anil Sharma, for killing a cyclist on the Nullarbor is detailed, with the victim's family expressing their grief. The South Australian government commits $674 million and adopts 129 recommendations from the Royal Commission into Domestic, Family and Sexual Violence, though one recommendation to ban smacking is rejected. Other stories include Adelaide's hottest day in nine months and a look at the Liberal Party's re-shuffled shadow cabinet just 99 days before the state election.
